            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> OK, I think you're referring to the workflow scope from personal access tokens, which is needed to modify workflows. Out of curiosity, which specific line from the update readme workflow did you need to modify? I took a quick glance at it but didn't see anything hardcoded.\r\n\r\nI update the last line of the readme.md file.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n> Yes, the \"read and write\" in the screenshot refers to the general permissions of GITHUB_TOKEN on workflows, not the \"workflow\" permission specifically which can only be accessed with a Personal Access Token. You can create a token yourself and request it to be included in the neovim-snap repo.\r\n> \r\n> That being said, the workflow permission is beyond cursed and I can't get it to work. My advice is to call an external shell script from your workflow and then modify that instead. Would this approach work?\r\n\r\nWorkflow tokens use to work perfectly for updating the last line until there was security changes at the organization level.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n",
